<table width="100%" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1"><tr><td class="menuhead">&nbsp;Question: How do traffic lights know you're there?</td></tr></table>
<BR>
<DIV style="text-align: center;"><img src="images/ask.gif" width="400" height="42" alt="Ask Datazoid" /></DIV>
<BR>
<span class="comment">Elfy asks:</span> <i>How do traffic lights know you're waiting for them to change?</i><BR>
<BR>
<span class="comment">Datazoid replies:</span><BR>
<BR>
This required less research than I'd initially thought. Somehow, I figured the road authority would have had some great secret about it, but..no, it's fairly stock standard. And yes, I'm playing this down somewhat.<BR>
<BR>
<span class="red">Short Answer:</span> Magnetic induction loops.<BR>
<BR>
<span class="red">Long Answer:</span> For the most part, Australian traffic lights (read: those in Sydney) operate by using magnetic induction loops to detect the presence of large metal objects. These, in the case of things moving over a road, are usually cars. Smaller objects, much to the chagrin of motorcyclists, aren't always detected. More on this soon.<BR>
<BR>
Magnetic induction loops are identified by saw slices or relaid squares of bitumen in the road surface, just before the stop-line at an intersection. The thing itself consists of a coil of wire beneath the surface, which detects the magnetic presence of a chunk of metal and sends a signal to the traffic control computer whatsit, which tells the lights what to do.<BR>
<BR>
The Sydney Coordinated Adaptive Traffic System (SCATS) is evidently part of the most advanced urban traffic control system in the world. It consists of 28 regional computers and a central computer, all of which work in unison to (try to) make traffic flow more smoothly. Generally this is accomplished by using the abovementioned roadway sensors to detect and monitor the flow of traffic, and then coordinate the light firing sequence to minimise delays. Cars are measured in groups, whereas individual cars generally have a longer wait. It's advised to attempt to remain in groups on the road to take advantage of this. (Whether this works in practise I do not know.) Additional advice is given that you should avoid running orange lights as the system will simply catch you up at the next red anyway, and that it's best to anticipate approaching the next light, and slow earlier rather than speeding along that stretch only to skid to a halt at the light. This evidently confuses the SCATS computer, and further slows the firing sequence. Nice to know Big Brother's keeping a look out, no?<BR>
<BR>
Motorcycles don't have enough metal components in their makeup to register in a magnetic induction loop. This usually means cyclists find themselves waiting at traffic lights longer than motorists. Several companies market powerful magnetic gizmos which can be mounted to motorcycle undersides to mimic the presence of a much larger magnetic field, such as that of a car. Whether these work, I also do not know. <BR>
<BR>
Happy motoring.<BR>
<BR>
<span class="comment">Addendum:</span><BR>
<BR>
<span class="red">Helmacron adds:</span> I was reading your explanation on the way the little cement things on the road send magnetic feedback loops and detect cars. Now, that sounds really nifty. But that's definately not universal. In Melbourne, it's pressure pads. I know it's pressure pads. Me and my friends tested one, once. We jumped on it and the lights changed. Then we didn't jump on it for a while and the lights didn't change. Then we jumped on it and they changed. Then we waited and then jumped on it when it wasn't ready and the lights changed. Then we left it alone and it didn't change. Then we jumped on it some more. Then we went looking for a hidden sensor because I thought there was a hidden LED sensor or something but there wasn't.<BR>
<BR>
And the other day, on the bus, this old bus driver was coaching a new bus driver and he was all "there's a pressure pad here, the lights change now... NOW... FUCKING NOW" and they changed. The man either is an expert in precognition or ESPiddle or he understood the inner workings of the road.<BR>
<BR>
Or whatever. Pressure pads in Melbourne.<BR>
<BR>
<span class="red">Datazoid responds:</span> Fair enough, then.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
